segments.text: Today is June 20, 1974.
We'll be interviewing Dr. James D. Lindsey, former head of the chemical engineering department.
Dr. Lindsey, if you would, would you tell us when and where you were born?
August the 24th, 1899, in Jamaica, Long Island, Jamaica, New York.
Queensborough.
Queensborough.
Could you tell us a little bit about your family, your father's name, your mother's name, and how your father was employed?
Well, my father was a sailor aboard a sailing ship.
When he left home, his mother remarried, and he was kind of forced out of the home, and he went as a cabin boy of the old days of the sailing ships and did quite a bit of sailing.
Then he came ashore.
and got a job packing boxes in the shipping department.
He was in that.
Where was this?
In New York City.
New York City.
And what was his full name?
James McCrossin Lindsey.
And your mother's name?
Ida Augusta Tucker was her maiden name.
Lindsey was her last name.
Can you tell us?
She grew up in New York, Brooklyn, New York.
Tell us a little bit about your boyhood days in New York.
Well, it was a country town when I was there.
One of the boys' radio was just coming in, and there was an older boy around the neighborhood that was interested, and he built his own radio receiving set, and I got so I could
read the code, and that is the call signals.
I couldn't read when they got going fast in the code signal.
But it was just a small town, country town.
It's grown up into large apartments around.
I had a sister that was one of the wanderers of the family.
went up to the North Coast, North Cape, and she got to be a school teacher.
And she taught down the Panama Canal, and she taught up in a hospital up in New York State.
She was a physical education teacher, and she got in giving remedial physical education to people who needed it.
She went all over the world on her vacations and also some jobs.
She and I, I had an older brother that died many when I was just a young boy, appendicitis.
Didn't know much about appendicitis in those days.
And so we grew up and I've lost track of most of the people.
There's one boy that
We bought a second-hand canoe and kept it down in Jamaica Bay, close to one of the present airports.
We sailed around Long Island.
In a canoe?
Yeah, there's a string of, just like down in Padre Island, there's a string of islands along the ocean shore, and then you've got the Long Island Sound on the inside.
So it's...
It's an inland waterway.
It's an inland waterway, yeah.
That sounds like a fascinating experience.
Well, it's entertaining at least.
And he is the only boy that I keep up with up there in Jamaica.
Are there any experiences that really stand out in your mind in your boyhood that might be interesting, anything that happened that you remember or recall?
We used to go coasting about Washington's birthday.
There was a very fine go almost for about a mile.
There was a hill, there's a ridge of hills along the backbone of Long Island.
And there was quite a hill in the back of our house.
And climb up to the top of it.
Anybody ski in those?
No.
No skiing?
No, no skiing.

It was way back on a hill back of us, and they had a very fine band, and every evening about 6 or 7 o'clock, they'd get out and parade with that band just to keep in practice, and we used to hear that coming over there.
So that area was really pretty much small-town America at the time.
Right.
This is right.
Could you tell us a little bit about your education?
Well, as my father was not an educated man, so when I finished high school, I didn't have any trend towards further education.
And I went to work for a pharmaceutical company called Pfizer, Charles Pfizer, Inc.
And as a lab boy, washing the dirty beakers in the lab and sweeping the floor and the like.
When was this that you went to work for Pfizer?
Well, it must have been right around 1918.
I'm not too certain.
See, I finished high school.
I go up with the years.
Right up with the close of World War I and without.
Yeah, I guess so.
See, each year, most of the year, I'm on the same date as the year.
74 in August, I get to be 75.
I can place things that way when things happen.
So I think I went to work for Pfizer about 1918.
Was that a large company then?
No, no.
It was quite a small company.
Very small.
Very small.
And I had a very fine boss.
What was his name?
James Nimrod Curry.
Very fine.
Dr. Curry, he's retired now in Vermont.
He must be about 96, 97 years old.
And he was like a father to me.
And the only man I know that has hair growing on the palms of his hands
He got a burn with bad, with phosphorus, very bad burn.
Phosphorus, white phosphorus is bad.

Tissue scars started growing together and they grafted on his stomach down on three sides and folded it down and then sewed it on three sides and kept it there for two weeks and then cut it off on the fourth side.
And the hair from his stomach still grows on the palm of his hand.
And he's, we've kept in touch.
Well, he was the one that urged me to go to school, go to night school, and I went to night school for a couple of years.
Where was this that you went to?
Columbia University.
Columbia.
Night school.
And he saw I could do that.
I was a willing worker, and he saw I could do that.

And then the next thing he urged me to do was to go to a regular day college rather than night school because you can only take one course at night and it would be so much quicker to work it out in a day college.
And because the middle western schools were so much cheaper than those in the east,
quote one of my friends, I went way out west to Michigan.
Anything across the Hudson River is out west to the New York people.
That's his advice.
Let me interrupt you here and get back to something that I want to ask.
Well, I don't want to take all the time.
No, no, no, this is fine.
We've got plenty of time.
The question I wanted to get back to is we skipped over your elementary and on up to high school education.
Jamaica High School.
Jamaica High School.
Jamaica High School.
And consider you've got to
a fairly good background there?
I think so.
A good one?
I think so.
Are there any particular people that stand out from those years that might have been inspirational in your life?
Well, there was a man by the name of Reynolds who was
He used to coach the rifle team, and that's how I got to know him.

Not that I was a real rifle expert, but he was a fine gentleman, and he was the one that urged me to try and do something first to get into a job, help me get this job over there at Pfizer's and the like.
He was always trying to keep the boys going towards higher education and the like.
How long did you work for Pfizer?
Well, they were very, very fine to me.
They were very fine.
And after I went to regular school at Michigan, they had a job for me every summer vacation.
How did you get out to Michigan?
Why there?
Why did you go there?
Why there?
Because I didn't know a soul, didn't know anything.
I'd never traveled.
We'd never traveled.
And Michigan was a good school.
Oh, yes.
That's what, on Dr. Curry's recommendation.
Oh, now he recommended you.
Yeah, we talked it over and I sent away and got a lot of catalogs.
I had a bunch of catalogs from all over.
And it was basically on Dr. Curry's recommendation.
And what year did you start Michigan?
Must have been about 1920.
Yeah, I finished in
And you'd already had a few courses.
A few courses.
It's helped out quite a bit.
Freshman chemistry and some of those things helped out quite a bit.
And then you went on to the University of Michigan majoring in?
First originally towards chemistry.
Got a B.S.
in chemistry.
I worked for Pfizer's every summer, and they really wanted me to go back to work for them.
They really wanted me to go to work on a permanent basis.
And I hated to turn them down, but I'd gotten the smell of fresh air.
See, when I worked for Pfizer's, I'd get in the subway, go up to Columbia, come on down on the subway, transfer to
It was an elevated railroad at that time, right back out to Jamaica on the elevated railroad.
And I'd done that for about three years, I guess.
Had three courses, three or four courses off.
Well, two years it was, 1918, 1920.
And I just didn't...
I got the smell of the fresh air out there at Michigan and made some very good friends out there.
In fact, one was the best man at my warden and another one...
I don't usually tell this.
He and I, the only time I've ever been in jail was with that old boy.
Don't put any of that in my memory.
His father was a ticket agent.
in a very small town in Michigan.
And I visited there.
One of the Thanksgiving or some vacations, I'd visit there.
His name was Dempsey.
We called him Jack because the real Jack Dempsey was just coming along then.
Wilmer Foster Dempsey.
His name was Wilmer?
W-I-L-M-E-R, Wilmer.
A family name, Wilmer Foster.
And so he was going with a girl out there in Ann Arbor.
Happened to be a nurse.
They had a nurse's training school there.
Can't you get a date for a friend of mine?
So he got a date from me, blind date, and she was a nurse.
And I went with her, but I didn't make out too well, a few dances and things like that and the like.
And I went to then this fellow, Roy Wilson,
who was another very good friend of mine.
His mother kept a rooming house.
She was a widow and kept a rooming house there.
We both went to work for the Standard Oil of Indiana in Whitey, Indiana, south of Chicago, about 30 or 40 miles south of Chicago.
Was this after you graduated?
After I got the B.S.
degree in chemical engineering.
Well, in pure chemistry.
Then...
I had a Model T Ford, and so about once a month or so, we'd go back and visit his mother, see his mother back in Ann Arbor, about 200 miles as I remember it.
Just by chance at all, walking down the street, I met this nurse who I'd had a few dates with,
And it started all up again.
And that's the girl that I married.
So chance has played a very important part in my life.
That's really amazing.
Well, we got married.
I decided that I wanted to get some more education instead of a BS degree.
I wanted to get into teaching, basically.
I wanted to get into teaching instead of working in industry.
You were still working for Standard Oil?
Standard Oil of Indiana.
And so looking around, if you want to get into teaching, go back and get an advanced degree.
And that's what governed my going back to school.
And when did you go back?
About 1930.
So you worked for Standard Oil for a while.
Well, one of my good friends, I went to work for a couple of years with the Kelvinator Corporation in Detroit.
That was when they were manufacturing refrigerators.
And he had such a much better job than the
Standard Oil Company that I went to work for.
It was about two years with Standard and about two years with... What did you do with Standard Oil?
What was your duties and responsibilities?
Well, first kind of a breaking in period in the laboratory, you know, and all that various tests and the like, and then working out in the plant, in the manufacturing plant.
Elias in between the...
the plant operators and the technical people inside.
Was this research or quality control?
Well, seeing that they were doing the right thing out in the plant, basically.
They changed the temperature and operating pressure.
In the early days, it was straight distillation.
Shell stills, just a bunch of tanks.
went to Berkshire and had a bill to fire on any of these tanks.
Didn't have catalytic crackers in those days.
Oh, no, they had none.
In fact, they didn't have any fractionation, where you'd get the different grades from the crude oil because it had a string of eight of these horizontal tanks.

in the first tank where you'd boil off the lighter stuff and pass it on to the next one and you'd boil off the heavier stuff and by the time you got to the last tank you had heavy rigid and each tank you'd condense so it was a heavier material quite a lengthy process oh yeah then they got

And that was just exactly, that was just the time when these fractionating towers came in, what they call a pipe still, where you have a big furnace, several times bigger than this room, pipes around the wall of the furnace, and just had a big gas or oil fire inside, and you look inside, the whole thing was hot, and yet that would heat these, the piping would pick up the heat,
Then you'd bring it to a distillation column and go into it and have trays.
And it would vaporize and you'd have reflux.
And on each tray, you'd get the lightest stuff off the top and the heaviest stuff off the bottom.
Instead of having a series of these steel tanks, great big steel tanks, 20 feet in diameter, we're taking a little fraction off.

you'd vaporize there, you'd put it in to this column, which may be 30 feet in diameter and maybe 40 feet high, 50 feet high, and you'd have trays in each one where the vapor would go up through caps, bubble caps, and the liquid, you'd put reflux down the top, and the liquid would come down from the top,
And the heavy residue would come out the bottom, and the overhead, light overhead, would come out the top.
And at different points in this tray, you'd take off cuts.
Instead of having a big, long series of great big tanks taking off the cuts, you'd take off cuts up and down this column.
When did this system come in?
That system came in...
Oh, about 1922, 23.
I went there in 24.
And they had it there.
And they were just starting.
Just starting.
In fact, they started up one of the biggest.
They started up a pipe still for the first time when I was there that first year.
Where was the location of this refinery?
Whiting, Indiana.
It's about 40 miles south of Chicago.
Then you went to Kelvinator.
What were your duties at Kelvinator?
watching manufacturing operations and doing research.
You did research.
Could you tell us a little bit about the research?
Oh, primarily corrosion resistance, just finding some of the best materials.
This is for the cooling unit?
Right.
Yeah, that's right.
And anything come out of this research that you did?
No.
Nothing in particular?
No, just pick the best materials that would stand out about it.
What were they using at that time?
Steel, but different alloy steel would be better.
Oh, my friend, Larry Phillips,
went up and just did fine in that organization.
He got to be on their board of directors, and he just did fine in Kelvinator.
And then you went back to school after Kelvinator.
And I went back to school about 1930.
And where was this, back at Michigan?
Michigan, back at Michigan.
And when did you receive your...
You received your
Ph.D. Ph.D., so you got your master's degree when?
In between, right in there.
And I converted to chemical engineering rather than pure chemistry.
I see.
Was this probably because of your industrial experience?
Yeah, that's right.
I made heavy water for a job.
Have you heard of heavy water?
Yes, I have, in conjunction with atomic experiments.
Well, you can...
One of my former, well, he was a teacher there, and when I went back to school, he was looking for somebody to come and help him work on a research project for making heavy water.
If you pass electricity through water, the heavy water, the heavy hydrogen will break up easier than the light hydrogen.
So he made a bunch of electrolytic cells
And it was my job just to keep the water level as you ran 24 hours a day.
And so I kept that.
And where was this?
At Michigan?
Yeah, Ann Arbor and Ann Arbor.
He was an organic chemist.
And you see, you can make materials out of hydrogen.
You know what an organic chemist, like methane is CH4.
And you use heavy hydrogen instead of light.
ordinary hydrogen, why those materials you make will have different properties than the other, the light hydrogen and so on.
And we've kept in touch with him, that man that was doing the research under whom I was working, making that heavy hydrogen for.
So then...
I finished there in 1934 and there were no, that's when we had a big depression.
There weren't any teaching jobs and so I took a job doing research on fertilizer.
Muscle Shoals originally had been a munitions plant in Alabama.
They converted that to a fertilizer plant.
It was just having to do with nitrates.
Right.
Phosphates, to phosphates primarily.
But nitrates and phosphates.
So I went down there to eat on, really.
And my boss knew I was looking for a teaching job when I went down there.
He came to me a year later, are you still interested in teaching?
And I said, yes.
So he said, well, a friend of mine is dean of engineering out in Idaho, and he's looking for a chemical engineering teacher.
And if you want it, you can have it.
So I said, I'll take it.
So then I really did go out way out west, as one of my friends said when I went to Michigan and taught there for a couple of years.
in Idaho, University of Moscow, Idaho.
Yes.
Is that Idaho State or University of Idaho?
University of Idaho.
And we have what's known as the American Society of Engineering Education, which is engineering teachers all over the country.
Most engineering would go to these meetings.
They usually, it's a cheap, I mean, they hold it at some college.
It's not a drinking national meeting like a good many of these national meetings are.
It's a hard working bunch.
So, I went to North Carolina State.
It's like a slave market.
In other words, people are looking.
So I went to North Carolina State for one year.
At the same time, I was talking to these people, but North Carolina State came through first.
I accepted that in Raleigh, North Carolina.
Two years, I have been very, very lucky in this deal here.
Two years as assistant professor at the University of Idaho, Moscow.
one year as associate professor at North Carolina State.
Came to Texas A&M as a full professor in a combined chemistry and chemical engineering department.
Three years as a full professor is not bad, is it?
You're right.
Well, just wait for another couple of years.
It was in a combined chemistry and chemical engineering department, and the dean of engineering was trying to get it spread.

It was in the School of Arts and Science, and I didn't realize what I was getting into, but there was a battle going on between the dean of engineering and the School of Arts and Science whether they should separate engineering into the School of Engineering or whether they should keep it in there.
And, boy, once I found out what was going on, I walked a straight and narrow path.
And then another year after that, I got to be made head of the department.
Okay, let's back up a minute before we get into that, before we jump into it.
Now, you spent a year at the University of North Carolina?
One year, right.
Then you came to A&M.
How did you go about getting to A&M?
Well, at the same time, I was talking to North Carolina.
That's one of these ASEE slave market deals.
I was talking with the Texas A&M.
Who were you talking to?
As I remember, it was a Mr. Gilchrist.
I think he was the one that actually hired me.
He was the one that actually hired me.
Now, it was a cockeyed operational because he hired me, but I was in the School of Arts and Science in the literary school.
And did you decide to come to A&M?
Did they offer you a more attractive position?
All of it was a boost in rank and a boost in pay.
And this was toward the end of the Depression now.
This is 37?
This is right at the tail end of the Depression.
Yeah, I think so.
And traditionally, this is the way chemical engineering
Originally, to go into the history of this stuff, originally they used to teach industrial chemistry in the School of Arts and Science.
How you made sulfuric acid and just a descriptive discussion of how you made various materials.
And then
The MIT people came out with a new idea, which they wrote a book called Unit Operations.
And here it studied different kinds of heat transfer.
Well, the first one is fluid flow.
Pressure drops through a pipe, whether you're pumping oil
or whether you're pumping water or whatever.
The same fundamentals will apply regardless of what you're pumping.
The same thing is true in heat transfer.
If you're heating something up, the same fundamentals would apply whether you're heating oil or whether you're heating water.
And that same idea was taken into all kinds of so-called unit operations, fluid flow,
heat transfer, distillation, the fundamentals of what you are doing, rather than the descriptive of how to make sulfuric acid.
And that idea was brand new in chemical engineering, in teaching.
Instead of a descriptive course, it was a how to do it course.
And that started MIT and, of course, the northern schools, Wisconsin.
Those schools picked it up and put it in, in chemical engineering.
But it took quite a while for the country boy schools, and I don't mean that he... No.
It took quite a while for that idea to get out to the smaller schools.
It's really kind of unusual, because here you had a school that was supposedly teaching the how-to-do of various things.
It was originally planned.
had agriculture teaching people how to do it.
It's unusual.
Well, there wasn't anybody had written a book on this so-called unit operations book put out by the MIT people.
It was brand new.
About 1920, that book came out.
Then you came here now in the fall of 38.
Fall of 38, as a full professor.
Right.
With full teaching load?
Yeah, I think so.
Well, a little bit of time supposed to be for research, but not very much in those days.
And at that time, I believe, T.O.
Walton was president.
Right.
That's right.
C.C.
Hedges was head of the chemistry department.
C.C.
Hedges.
Cut the
Well, Mr. Gilchrist, who was Dean of Engineering, wanted to get the chemical engineering taught in the School of Engineering under him, rather than in the School of Arts and Science.
So he approached me, would I be willing?
And once I told him I'd be willing, but I couldn't take any sides in the matter.
And he understood that.
And so they used to have a board of directors meeting to graduate, legally graduate the students.
And then they'd have a reception for the parents after the graduation.
And all the staff used to go to that reception to meet the parents of the students.
So Mr. Gilchrist beckoned me over.
You're going to be working for me this summer.
So the same board of directors that had graduated the students, they had decided to separate
the department.
So he sort of rammed it through the board of directors.
Oh yes, he was for that all the time.
Do you think he had any opposition to forming a chemical engineering department?
Oh yes, the old boy Hedges, Professor C.C.
Hedges, didn't want to let it go.
He didn't want to lose his chemical engineering section.
That's right.
It's only normal, I suppose.
And then this was what, 39 and 40?
No, about 41, I think.
I think it was about 41.
And Mr. Gilchrist, the old, had the old geology building.
I don't know whether it's...
They taught petroleum in it for a long time.
That one used to have a tower on it.
Used to have a water tank in it.
Right, right, a water tank inside of that tower, right.
And so he said, we'll put you over there this summer, but it won't be long before we have a regular chemical engineering building for you.
About two or three years it'll take to get us separated.
And that was from about 41 to about three or four years ago when they built this new engineering building up on the corner, maybe five years ago.
So we were in that old geology building for many years.
And then they built a... Every time somebody moved out, I'd get my foot in the door to get a few extra rooms.
They built a very nice...
It used to be petroleum, too, in there.
Chemical engineering has to do with the distilling of the oil.
The petroleum engineering has to do hunting the oil, finding the oil, and getting it up out of the ground and transporting it through their pipelines.
And then chemical engineers take over at a refinery
and have to do with the separation of the products.
When was the department accredited?
Do you remember?
Say, no, I don't.
I'd have to, it was, we went through a long, hard series of troubles in getting us accredited.
First was, there's a lot of things, getting the equipment and getting enough staff and I don't recall.
I'd have to look it up.
Let's drop back a minute now.
We've got up into the 40s.
When you first came here, do you have any impressions of, say, President Walton?
He was here until 1943.
Well, I thought he was a very good president.
Did you have any personal relationship with him at all?
Oh.
Did you ever get called into his office to talk to him?
I sure did.
Harrington, too.
One of the things that I inherited was cotton seed.
They do a lot of cotton seed, growing cotton here and making cotton seed oil and chicken feed out of what's left after you squeeze
So that was going on when I came, but I inherited a lot of that.
And so we had this short course in cottonseed oil.
And it wasn't too large.
About 80 and 90 people would come to it.
Is it in the summertime?
Usually, yes.
And then...
So we'd had that.
I'd had that experience with that cottonseed short course.
Then I started a, well, I'd take our students out on inspection trips.
And things had changed so much since I was a boy in a refinery, why they had automatic
recording instruments and control instruments.
If you wanted to change a valve or read a gauge, you'd have to climb a steel ladder to read it and twist the valve yourself.
Whereas I'd come down here quite a few years later, and they had recording instruments and control.
You didn't have to do all of that.
You had a little house, a regular house, where they had these recording instruments in.
And so I thought we should teach some of that.
And I didn't know anything about automatic control or the like.
And I wrote to a bunch of companies that made these instruments, asking for their catalogs and information.
And one afternoon, a chap showed up in my office.
from one of these big companies and said, we've had requests for information from all kinds of people, but we never had a request from a college professor.
What did you want to know for?
So I told him what I had in mind of teaching that stuff in our classes, and he thought that was a very fine idea and agreed to work with me.
And then he said, well, it sure would be good if we could get some of these older people
acquainted with the operations of these instruments, as well as your new students just coming through.
So having been associated with this oilseed course, I said, well, maybe we can do that, too.
And so we started an instrumentation short course.
And it was very, very elementary at the start.
We'd meet in the classrooms.
have the exhibits in the halls of the building, and it has developed very, very fine.
That's still going on?
It's still going on.
And the new student center in 1950, when we had the student center built, why, that was a big help.
And we get about 600, 700 people attend it now, and they come from all over the country.
It was the first one that got started, even before there's an Instruments Society of America that got started now.
Do you remember the year you held your first meeting?
Oh, I think I'd have to look this up, too, about 41, 42.
I can get all of this factual material.
And...
So it's mighty fine.
I've made mighty fine friends in that organization.
Well, where I got to know these presidents a little bit more, as you know, a lot of these guys from industry like to have a drink.
And there's a lot of salesmen around.
And they're selling the instruments.
And the people from the big companies will be using the instruments.
And so I got called down to the president's office.
They found five bottles, whiskey bottles, in your wastebaskets in the room.
What room is this?
In the student center here on the campus.
And there's not supposed to be any... What president was this in the country?
Well, I think it was Walton was the first one, and it was just when Harrington was taken over.
And Harrington was a teacher in the chemistry department.
Well, let's see.
Walton was here until 1943, and then Bolton until 1944, and then Gib Gilchrist until 1948, and Bolton again, and then Harrington the first time in 1950.
Yeah.
Well, anyway, every little while this thing would happen.
So I had gotten called down there.
I know Harrington, he sure didn't want to do it because he lived down the street from me before he got to be president.
But he had to do it.
And when I got told that they found him in the wastebaskets of the room, I put out the word.
If any time you guys empty a bottle here on the campus, why, put it in your suitcase and take it home with you.
And I never had any trouble from then on.
So that's how I originally got to...
I mean, I got called down to the president's office a couple of times.
One was real bad.
There was one...
over in the board of directors house.
And one of the guys really got intoxicated over in the board.
You don't remember our old student center across the street from the, remember when they crossed the street from the mess hall?
right next to the old president's house.
This used to be the Aggieland Inn?
Aggieland Inn, yeah.
I've seen pictures.
It was torn down right as I Yeah.
Well, anyway, several years ago.
Well, they used to have displays in there.
It was quite elementary.
But it'swe've changed things up and hold them now at the end of the semester.
Well, digress a little bit here.
What do you remember of the end of the Depression here on the campus?
Was there many hardships from the teaching faculty?
Did anybody know there was a Depression going on here?
I don't remember too much about that.
Was it an island of relative prosperity in a country that was having hard times?
We had a harder time to get jobs for the students.
I worked very closely with the students in getting jobs.
That was something that I was always...
good relations with the students.
In fact, the matter is, they gave me an automobile when I retired.
Yes, I know.
Well, anyway, working hard, that was the hardest thing, is getting jobs for the students.
But I don't recall that we had
trouble.
See, I was here and our staff was pretty well fixed.
